textDisplay: Movies like this are pretty common in India, where the Court-room is often considered the last resort for the ordinary masses to win justice against cruel but powerful elements. But I never could have expected such a movie from PR China, portraying the helplessness of common people against the cruelty and wrongdoings of well-connected and influential villains. I guess movies like this are beautiful because of their honesty and empathy: they speak for the Small Common Man who often is the victim of injustice, but has nowhere to go for redressal.
textOriginal: Movies like this are pretty common in India, where the Court-room is often considered the last resort for the ordinary masses to win justice against cruel but powerful elements. But I never could have expected such a movie from PR China, portraying the helplessness of common people against the cruelty and wrongdoings of well-connected and influential villains. I guess movies like this are beautiful because of their honesty and empathy: they speak for the Small Common Man who often is the victim of injustice, but has nowhere to go for redressal.

textDisplay: This movie was actually pretty entertaining. Put it on my second monitor but ended up just watching it. Cheese here and there, and Rock going to Rock, but I think it had some good heart for Christmas, was entertaining, and that's all that really matters. Outside of this, who decided to make the reindeer "female"? And please don't go quoting some science guide stating that male reindeer lose their antlers in the winter when Santa's reindeer are magical and can fly... I didn't find the movie to be woke, and had no problem with the diversity presented. Only thing that brought me out of it was having all the reindeers be female. :/

textDisplay: The first act of this movie was the best part. The way they set up the mood, atmosphere, and tension was great. Just all around gorgeous lighting and shot framing. Sadly, everything falls apart after that. Act III was an abomination. Was so trilled for a good detective story with our interesting lead, but it all went to supernatural garbage. Nicolas Cage felt absolutely ridiculous and ruined this film. The moment he appeared in his own scene, I was completely removed from the experience. During Act I, I thought I was witnessing the next "Silence of the Lambs" or "Seven", but it doesn't even go near greats like those. Beautifully shot, but zero substance.

textDisplay:
Lately, Iâ€™ve been thinking a lot about the idea of American exceptionalismâ€”especially the belief that Americans would somehow be uniquely resistant to authoritarianism. Films like Civil War by Alex Garland tap into that myth. They portray bold uprisings, states breaking away in defiance, people rising up en masse to fight tyranny. But honestly, Iâ€™m not convinced thatâ€™s how things would really go.

When I look at the political climate in the U.S. now, especially with the return of figures like Donald Trump whoâ€™ve shown clear authoritarian tendencies, what I see isnâ€™t widespread resistanceâ€”itâ€™s resignation. A lot of people just seem to be keeping their heads down, hoping things will pass. Thereâ€™s a real sense of fear, weariness, and even helplessness. The courts, the media, the institutions that are supposed to hold things in checkâ€”they often seem either overwhelmed or complicit. That doesnâ€™t lead to rebellion; it leads to quiet compliance.

And this idea that Americans are somehow fundamentally different from people in other countries? That theyâ€™ll always stand up for liberty while others cower? That just doesnâ€™t hold water. People everywhere are people. When faced with fear, most will try to protect their families, avoid trouble, and wait things out. Itâ€™s not necessarily cowardiceâ€”itâ€™s just a survival instinct.

Revolutions, historically, donâ€™t always come from noble courage in the face of tyranny. They come when people have no other option, or when a critical mass sees an opening. But most of the time, especially in the early stages of authoritarianism, people try to adapt. They rationalize, they withdraw, they stay quiet.

So while Civil War might capture the emotional intensity of a fractured America, I donâ€™t think it reflects the reality of how resistance plays out. If things keep sliding further, I suspect the reaction wonâ€™t be some dramatic uprisingâ€”but more likely a slow, uncertain acquiescence. And thatâ€™s what I find really chilling.

textDisplay: Saw the movie today on Hulu.  Actually surprised it went to stream so quickly and for free.  The beginning was a little rough and hard to draw my attention.  I didnâ€™t see what all the hype was about for either the movie or Chalamet but more towards the middle, I got drawn in, mainly to the story and life of  Bob Dylan and Chalmetâ€™s acting improved.  I canâ€™t tell where he gained 20 pounds except maybe his face but he really didnâ€™t need to gain any weight because at same age, Dylan was just as skinny.  You love the story but horrible how Dylan rotated women like we rotate our outfits.  He even took Joan to Sylvieâ€™s apartment the first time.  But the ending was good.  Basically form your own path.  He canâ€™t forget folk music did give him his start and everyone involved who let him in door and for some people thatâ€™s what they wanted.  Iâ€™m glad he gave Newport at least one folk song.  This movie is along the lines of 1979â€™s The Rose.  Not same story but about a musician.  If youâ€™ve never seen that movie, I would recommend.  For people who didnâ€™t know Bob Dylan, good movie.  It would have been a fun movie to be cast in, different time era and especially for Chalamet to sing, play guitar and see what being a superstar is all about.  But I wasnâ€™t â€œwowedâ€ like everyone else.  Almost anyone could play that part and he was given 5 years to learn guitar, sing, figure out voice and study Bob Dylan.  Not to mention he does appear to be instrument and language inclined as he learned piano for another movie and did study at a prestigious arts high school (advantage). Thousands of dollars not gone to waste.  Itâ€™s one of those movies you should see at least once.  I thought Elle Fanning did a great job in her role which no one talks about and Joan Baez sang great.  At least toward the end, finally Chalamet and Fanning had some on screen chemistry.  Chalamet struggles with on screen chemistry except for a select few that I think he wants to date in real life.  I didnâ€™t realize Sylvie was portraying Suze.  For his first serious 4 year relationship, the movie didnâ€™t really portray it that way.  I never saw at the end if Chalamet gave Woody back his harmonica or not. Before this movie, I didnâ€™t know â€œfolk musicâ€ was about social justice.  I thought it was just another music genre.

textDisplay:
Low and behold, itâ€™s already 1 year old!!!

The filmmakers manage to make the movie stand on its own terms without blatantly resembling the original 
There's minor callbacks here and there but it's really about this young woman dealing with her possible hysteria interfering with her godly duties 
Nell Tiger Free gives a fantastic, gut-wrenching performance being appropriately conflicted There's a heavy dose of atmosphere, gnarly-looking visuals, and some truly memorable sequences adding to the grotesque body horror 
It's incredible that Stevenson was able to pull off as much as she did particularly with one scene so graphic she avoided an NC-17 rating And when they do explain the reasoning for this unholy birth taking place it totally turns everything around 
To them this rising of the son of the devil might be the answer to send the ignorant back to their faith, making change without resorting to violence, erase the need for secularism wiping the slate clean as it were, how do we control people who no longer believe (by creating something to fear) 
There's also subtle comments and motifs on women's reproductive rights and bodily autonomy in the name of the holy word being quite contemporary 
The first film is superior in many ways and this does take a while to get going being 2 hours but I'm so thankful this one created a very good bridge to what was established prior while still being an effective religious horror tale 
Maybe more 'Omen' films are on the way that can bring back some staying power to a nearly 50 year old franchise
textOriginal:
Low and behold, itâ€™s already 1 year old!!!

The filmmakers manage to make the movie stand on its own terms without blatantly resembling the original 
There's minor callbacks here and there but it's really about this young woman dealing with her possible hysteria interfering with her godly duties 
Nell Tiger Free gives a fantastic, gut-wrenching performance being appropriately conflicted There's a heavy dose of atmosphere, gnarly-looking visuals, and some truly memorable sequences adding to the grotesque body horror 
It's incredible that Stevenson was able to pull off as much as she did particularly with one scene so graphic she avoided an NC-17 rating And when they do explain the reasoning for this unholy birth taking place it totally turns everything around 
To them this rising of the son of the devil might be the answer to send the ignorant back to their faith, making change without resorting to violence, erase the need for secularism wiping the slate clean as it were, how do we control people who no longer believe (by creating something to fear) 
There's also subtle comments and motifs on women's reproductive rights and bodily autonomy in the name of the holy word being quite contemporary 
The first film is superior in many ways and this does take a while to get going being 2 hours but I'm so thankful this one created a very good bridge to what was established prior while still being an effective religious horror tale 
Maybe more 'Omen' films are on the way that can bring back some staying power to a nearly 50 year old franchise

textDisplay:
This is probably one of the worse anime movies I have seen! Most of the damn movie was a recap! Who recaps for 45 minutes to an hour. Just as I thought the movie was gonna pick up and get really good it was over. It sucks because the first demon slayer movie was excellent. This move just seems like they wanted money. The only good fight scenes was from the recap. This movies sucked and I am for sure not going to see another demon slayer movie after this garbage. I can wait for Hulu or one of the streaming companies to get it. 
It's hard to see that people have given this movie good reviews. Any movie with a 45 minute to an hour recap is trying to fill the gap they couldn't fill. This shouldn't of been a movie and they know that. When they actually start the movie so much time has passed so they pretty much just talk heal and go to training. There wasn't enough to put into the movie so they recapped most of the movie.

Oh and the dumbest part of the whole movie is that nezuko is a sun god now! Just poof the sun don't hurt her. Now since I have seen the show I know wtf is going on for everyone else this part is so dumb. While recapping for an hour you didn't think you should fill in the back on that as well. I mean it's only an hour recap lol.

Part 2 of the movie let's recap the first movie for an hour and then train for 30 minutes over done. I saved you all money and now you don't need to see part 2!!!

On a side note people are like it's amazing to see in theaters. First off with how cheap a TV for "60 is it's pretty hard to see going to a theater being better. Next they are like the sound. This is what happens when your theater room in your house has them small speakers or just has a sound bar....maybe invest in some good quality sound. Our movies at my place sound almost better than theaters.

LOL, people who are saying the trailer points out it is a recap. Nothing in the trailer says it is a recap the whole movie. It for sure trick you to think they are making a new movie. He also indicates this is for the fans......I think that was a typo I think that was supposed to say money. Either way the official trailer for sure makes it look like a new movie and not a recap. I shouldn't have to go read about it to find this out the trailer should show me but it doesn't. So to have people giving it 1 star makes 100% sense only them demon slayer nerds would know as they research it like it's something important.

I know I said it once but the animation is just like it is on the show and when you have a budget like them anyone can make it look that good. 

P.S.

Everyone that is like the animation is amazing and can't be beat. First off they have such a high budget that any anime movie with a budget like this will look amazing. Lastly the whole thing looked no different from the episode are people seeing stuff I am not seeing? To me it sounds like this show has a lot of fans that like to kiss a$$. Tbh I hate the maker of this bc it is clear he just did this for money and not the fans as you can clearly see he maybe spent an hour making this movie as most of it is a recap. Demon slayer lost a lot of respect from me due to this movie.

1 year old!

It's about as straightforward as you'd expect 
Dog lovers will rejoice although it takes a long while for the actual dog to show up with our main leads
The human players aren't very deep either
I was truly getting teary eyed near the end though and the cinematography is lovely looking at the jungle terrain
There's lots of stuff in here about redemption and humility
Maybe would've worked better as a tv flick but as it is the film is a decent underdog story to say the least

textDisplay:
We hate most movies these days. Many faith based movies are cringe or poor acting. Some are purposefully a wolf in sheep's clothing so we just dont watch many movies and few faith movies, BUT THIS!!!! This movie was inspired by God! The acting was great! Cast was great!  The story was outstanding! The message was long over due and done properly. This and The War Room are movies needed. No red flags. No cring moments or poor acting! Some very astounding acting scenes by many. Some scenes are not easy to pull off but they pulled them off flawlessly. You forget you are watching a movie because the acting is well done.

I hope these ppl make another one. The War Room, The Forge......God is Not Dead series...Risen....Abt 3 Kevin Sorbo movies...Those are worth having before others....but, be clear,The Forge is profoundly well done.

Thank you.

textDisplay: Anora is not a love story, and I've seen many critics only focusing on the relationships aspect of this movie. Instead Anora is a movie about the multiple and parallel realities that immigrants live in the US. Some struggle to integrate and erase their background (like Annie vs Anora), others stay true to who they are (like Igor), others really manage to integrate and live an almost american life (like Toros), and others simply live as if the world is theirs no matter where they are (the Zakharov family).
textOriginal: Anora is not a love story, and I've seen many critics only focusing on the relationships aspect of this movie. Instead Anora is a movie about the multiple and parallel realities that immigrants live in the US. Some struggle to integrate and erase their background (like Annie vs Anora), others stay true to who they are (like Igor), others really manage to integrate and live an almost american life (like Toros), and others simply live as if the world is theirs no matter where they are (the Zakharov family).

textDisplay:
I cried at the end. Full out sob. I had a headache most of the movie because I didnâ€™t expect it to be so chaotic with the yelling and talking over each other. Iâ€™ve lived a similar life so maybe I was subconsciously triggered. 

By the end, I related. Iâ€™m dealing with a 21 yr old loss of a relationship where my ex and his family exploited me and turned the tables. Ruined my little family. 

You donâ€™t have to be a sex worker to relate to the feeling of people wanting to trash you and make you feel like trash because you donâ€™t have or come from where they come from. 

In my life, I donâ€™t have a big, full family. My chosen family was my life. My ex, flipped the switch on me, going so far as to pretend he didnâ€™t know me in public. 

He might as well burned me alive. Sounds dramatic. But when you believe in and are invested in your life to the extent I was- you canâ€™t help but feel that pain- 

I wish I had someone hold and hug me through this low era of my life. I just feel like life has been generally hard. Tired of that. 

Love and light to those struggling. We all want to be loved and accepted. To know theyâ€™re enough. Simple. Yet missing in so many of our lives.

textDisplay: I saw an review which had an interesting take on the final scene.  When Igor gave Anora the ring, her "gratitude" manifested itself by her reverting to what she knew best which was sex as a job with no emotional involvement.  When Igor, who clearly had developed admiration and feelings for her, wanted something more than passionless sex by rote and tried to kiss her, she, still in her "job" mode instinctively pulled away.  But then, maybe she realized that Igor was "safe", she let him pull her into his arms and all of the anger, feelings of loss and sheer grief came flooding out. What this means for the two of them, the director left to the imagination of the audience.  Much as the possibility of Anora and Igor becoming a thing is intriguing, it probably can't happen. Maybe the experience has changed both of them but Anora likely has more trust issues than ever and Igor is a spoke in the Russian mob wheel and you don't walk away from that in one piece, especially since Ivan's mother might look for any excuse to order a hit on Anora.  My own opinion?  The is one great f-ing movie, Mikey Madison more than deserved her Oscar and it was wonderful that Yura Borisov's excellent and very nuanced work was recognized with a nomination,

textDisplay:
What I liked about borderlands that it was hard-core SCI FI the way you'd imagine it to look like in a tough environment with hard to deal with aliens yet with incredibly powerful weapons. Everything looks futuristic, yet also beaten and battleworn. Due to high cost but high reward, you'd imagine only the toughest out of the probably hundreds of billions of people that live to even consider going to the borderlands. Due to 100% lessaiz fair capitalism on the borderlands, you're either rich, or you die by the way side. There is no state. There is no police. There is no constitution. There's no rights or laws; there's only money, and weapons. You make hard cash or nobody gives a fuck.  I got nothing from that in the trailer.

And the king of the jungle, the richest guy with the biggest weapon, who's in the process of building a de facto dictatorship, with nothing but power he got through drones, money, & artillery, choiling in a spaceship floating above all & sending down drones when something doesn't go his way - Handsom Jack, the best character of them all, is missing.

textDisplay: I've finally watched this movie - miscast, misdirected, miserable.    I've seen the movie and still it doesn't make sense.  There's a search for three parts of a lost key that might have been ordered it from Argos, found it in a back drawer, and went next door and murdered the neighbours for the third part.  The dialogue is generally unfunny trash, characterisation across the board is execrable, it rips off far better films like Star Wars, and it does the worst thing you can do in a movie like this by having villains who are badly written and incompetent.  Scenes do jump cuts with no explanation.  Should be preserved to show film students hat not to do with a large budget and an experienced cast.
